\begin{align} L(y_i | p_i) &= (1 - p_i) \cdot \left( \frac{p_i}{1 - p_i} \right)^{y_i}\\ &= (1 - p_i) \cdot \text{exp} \left( y_i \cdot \color{#FF6666}{ \text{log} \left( \frac{p_i}{1 - p_i} \right) } \right) \end{align}

\begin{align*} \eta_i &= \text{log} \left( \frac{p_i}{1 - p_i} \right) \\ &= \text{logit} (p_i) \end{align*}

$g$logit function.

\begin{align*} \text{log} \left( \frac{p_i}{1 - p_i} \right) &= x_i^t \beta \\ \frac{p_i}{1 - p_i} &= e^{x_i^t \beta} \\ p_i &= (1 - p_i) \cdot e^{x_i^t \beta} \\ \left( 1 + e^{x_i^t \beta} \right) p_i &= e^{x_i^t \beta} \\ p_i &= \frac{e^{x_i^t \beta}}{1 + e^{x_i^t \beta}} \\ &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x_i^t \beta}} \end{align*}

$i$$p_i$ \begin{align*} L_i(y_i | p_i) &= \text{exp} \left\{y_i \cdot \color{red}{\log\left( \frac{p_i}{1-p_i}\right)} + \color{blue}{ \log(1 - p_i)} \right\} \\ \end{align*}

  • $\color{red}{\log\left( \frac{p_i}{1-p_i}\right)}$: the projection of the regression vector $x_i^t \beta$.

  • $\color{blue}{\log(1 - p_i)}$:

\begin{align*} p_i &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x_i^t \beta}} \\ 1 - p_i &= \frac{ e^{-x_i^t \beta}}{1 + e^{-x_i^t \beta}} \\ &=\frac{ 1}{1 + e^{x_i^t \beta}} \\ \log(1 - p_i) &= -1 \cdot \log(1 + e^{x_i^t \beta}) \end{align*}

: \begin{align*} l(y_i | x_i, \beta) &= \sum_i \left(y_i \cdot x_i^t \beta - \log(1 + e^{x_i^t \beta}) \right) \\ &= y^t X \beta - \log(1 + e^{X\beta}) \end{align*}

=0

\begin{align*} \nabla_\beta l(y_i | x_i, \beta) &= \nabla y^t X \beta - \nabla \log(1 + e^{X\beta}) \\ &= X^t y - \nabla \log(1 + e^{X\beta}) \end{align*}

$\beta_k$

\begin{align*} \frac{\partial}{\partial \beta_k} \log(1 + e^{X \beta}) &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{X \beta}} \cdot x_k^t \cdot e^{X \beta} \end{align*}

$p$:

\begin{align*} \frac{1}{1 + e^{X \beta}} \cdot x_k^t \cdot e^{X \beta} &= x_k^t p \end{align*}

\begin{align*} \nabla \log(1 + e^{X\beta}) &= X^t p \end{align*}

\begin{align*} \nabla_\beta l(y_i | x_i, \beta) &= X^t y - \nabla \log(1 + e^{X\beta}) \\ &= X^t y - X^t p \\ &= X^t (y - p) \end{align*}

Newton-Raphson$f$ \begin{align*} \beta^{(k+1)} &= \beta^{(k)} - \frac{f\,'(\beta^{(k)})}{f\,''(\beta^{(k)})} \end{align*}

\begin{align*} \beta^{(k+1)} &= \beta^{(k)} - H^{-1}(\beta^{(k)}) \nabla f\,(\beta^{(k)}) \end{align*}

$ H $Hessian $f$

Hessian

$X^t (y - p)$Hessian$X^t p$

Hessian

\begin{align*} \frac{\partial^2 l(\beta)}{\partial \beta_j \partial \beta_k} &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \beta_j} \sum_i x_{i,k} \cdot p_i \\ &= \sum_i x_{i,k} \cdot \frac{\partial p_i}{\partial \beta_j} \\ \end{align*}

$p_i$$\beta_j$ \begin{align*} \frac{\partial p_i}{\partial \beta_j} &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \beta_j} \frac{1}{1+e^{-x_i^t \beta}} \\ &= \frac{-1}{(1+e^{-x_i^t \beta})^2} \cdot -1 \cdot x_{i,j} \cdot e^{-x_i^t \beta} \\ &= x_{i,j} \cdot \left(\frac{1}{1+e^{-x_i^t \beta}} \right) \cdot \left(\frac{e^{-x_i^t \beta}}{1+e^{-x_i^t \beta}} \right) \\ &= x_{i,j} \cdot p_i \cdot (1 - p_i) \\ &= x_{i,j} \cdot \text{Var}(y_i) \end{align*}

Hessian \begin{align*} H l(y | x_i, \beta) &= - X^t D X \end{align*}

$D$ $n\times n$$p_i\cdot(1-p_i)$

Newton-Raphson

\begin{align*} \beta^{(k+1)} &= \beta^{(k)} - H^{-1}(\beta^{(k)}) \nabla f\,(\beta^{(k)}) \\ &= \beta^{(k)} + (X^t D X)^{-1} X^t (y - p^{(k)}) \end{align*}

$z$

\begin{align*} \beta^{(k+1)} &= (X^t D X)^{-1} (X^t D X) \beta^{(k)} + (X^t D X)^{-1} X^t (y - p^{(k)}) \\ &= (X^t D X)^{-1} X^t D (X \beta^{(k)} + D^{-1} (y - p) ) \\ &= (X^t D X)^{-1} X^t D z \end{align*}

-

$$ \beta^{(k+1)} = \underset{b}{\operatorname{argmin}} \left\{ || D^{1/2} (z - Xb) ||_2^2 \right\} $$

# Fit GLM IRWLS
beta <- rep(0,p)
for (k in 1:10) {
  prob <- 1 / (1 + exp(-X %*% beta))
  D <- diag(as.numeric(prob*(1-prob)))
  z <- X %*% beta + (y - prob) / diag(D)
  beta <- qr.solve(crossprod(X, D %*% X), crossprod(X, D %*% z))
  print(sum((beta - coef(out))^2))
}

Logistic regression & Neural networks¶

Logistic regression

Activation functions

  • Logistic regression
\begin{align*} \text{logit} (p_i) &= \text{log} \left( \frac{p_i}{1 - p_i} \right) \\ \text{logit}^{-1} \left( X \beta \right) & = \frac{1}{1 + e^{- X \beta}} \end{align*}
  • Neural networks
$$\sigma(x \cdot w + b) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-(x \cdot w + b)}}$$

The inverse of the logit function is the sigmoid function .

Feed-forward network ()

  • RNN

weightsbias?

logistic regression SVM

cost function ( loss function )

squared error loss: \begin{align*} C(w, b) &= \frac{1}{2n} \sum_i (y_i - \widehat{y}(x_i) )^2 \end{align*}

Optimization problem & gradient descent

\begin{align*} w_{k+1} &= w_k - \eta \cdot \nabla_w C \\ b_{k+1} &= b_k - \eta \cdot \nabla_b C \end{align*}
  • learning rate, $\eta > 0$

Decomposable cost function

\begin{align*} C &= \frac{1}{n} \sum_i C_i \end{align*}

For the individual costs $C_i$ of the $i$'th sample.

Decomposable cost function

$M \subseteq \{1, 2, \ldots n \}$$m$. \begin{align*} \frac{\sum_{i \in M} \nabla C_i}{m} &\approx \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n \nabla C_i}{n} \approx \nabla C \end{align*}

Stochastic gradient descent (SGD)

  • Stochastic gradient descent uses this idea to speed up the process of doing gradient descent.

  • the input data are randomly partitioned into disjoint groups $M_1, M_2, \ldots, M_{n/m}$.

  • update

\begin{align*} w_{k+1} &= w_k - \frac{\eta}{m} \sum_{i \in M_1} \nabla C_i \\ w_{k+2} &= w_{k+1} - \frac{\eta}{m} \sum_{i \in M_2} \nabla C_i \\ &\vdots \\ w_{k+n/m+1} &= w_{k+n/m} - \frac{\eta}{m} \sum_{i \in M_{n/m}} \nabla C_i \end{align*}

Each set $M_j$ is called a mini-batch and going through the entire dataset as above is called an epoch .

Stochastic gradient descent (SGD)

main tuning parameters:

  • size of themini-batch ($m$)
  • the learning rate ($\eta$)
  • number of epochs (E)

OLSSGD

SGD Examples: OLS

\begin{align*} f(\beta) &= \frac{1}{n} \cdot \sum_i f_i(\beta) \\ &= \frac{1}{n} \cdot \sum_i (y_i - x_i \beta)^2 \\ &= \frac{1}{n} \cdot \sum_i (y_i^2 + \beta^t x_i^t x_i \beta - 2 y_i x_i \beta) \end{align*}

SGD Examples: OLS

The gradient of $f$: \begin{align*} \nabla f &= \frac{1}{n} \cdot \sum_i f_i(\beta) \\ &= \frac{1}{n} \cdot \sum_i \nabla f_i(\beta) \\ &= \frac{2}{n} \cdot \sum_i (x_i^t x_i \beta - x_i^t y_i) \end{align*}

$m$mini-batch $M$ \begin{align*} \nabla f &\approx \frac{2}{m} \cdot \sum_{i \in M} (x_i^t x_i \beta - x_i^t y_i) \end{align*}

eta <- 0.01
b <- rep(0, p)
err <- rep(NA, nrow(miniBatchIndex))
for (j in 1:nrow(miniBatchIndex)) {
  ind <- miniBatchIndex[j,]
  gradMini <- (2/m) * ((t(X[ind,]) %*% X[ind,]) %*% b - t(X[ind,]) %*% y[ind])
  b <- b - eta * gradMini
  err[j] <- max(abs(b - betaOls))
}

plot(err, log="y", type="l", xlab="iteration")
grid()

eta <- 0.01
b <- rep(0, p)
E <- 10
err <- rep(NA, nrow(miniBatchIndex)*E)
for (k in 1:E) {
  miniBatchIndex <- matrix(sample(1:n),ncol=m)
  for (j in 1:nrow(miniBatchIndex)) {
    ind <- miniBatchIndex[j,]
    gradMini <- (1/m) * (2 * (t(X[ind,]) %*% X[ind,]) %*% b - 2 * t(X[ind,]) %*% y[ind])
    b <- b - eta * gradMini
    err[j+(k-1)*nrow(miniBatchIndex)] <- max(abs(b - betaOls))
  }
}

plot(err, log="y", type="l", axes=FALSE, xlab="epoch")
box()
axis(2)
axis(1, at=(0:E)*nrow(miniBatchIndex), 0:E)
abline(v=(1:E)*nrow(miniBatchIndex))

Stochastic gradient descent (SGD)

  • Stochastic gradient descent uses this idea to speed up the process of doing gradient descent.

  • the input data are randomly partitioned into disjoint groups $M_1, M_2, \ldots, M_{n/m}$.

  • update

\begin{align*} w_{k+1} &= w_k - \frac{\eta}{m} \sum_{i \in M_1} \nabla C_i \\ w_{k+2} &= w_{k+1} - \frac{\eta}{m} \sum_{i \in M_2} \nabla C_i \\ &\vdots \\ w_{k+n/m+1} &= w_{k+n/m} - \frac{\eta}{m} \sum_{i \in M_{n/m}} \nabla C_i \end{align*}
  • $\nabla C_i$?

back-propagation¶

  • $w^{l}_{j,k}$ the weight of node $k$ in layer $l-1$ as applied by node $j$ in layer $l$.

  • $b^l_j$ the bias of node $j$ of layer $l$

  • $z^l_j$ The weighted input emitted from node $j$ in layer $l$logsitic regression $X \beta$

  • $a^l_j$ $a^l_j= \sigma(z^l_j) $

\begin{align*} a^l_j &= \sigma(z^l_j) \\ &= \sigma(\sum_k w^l_{jk} a_k^{l-1} + b^l_j) \end{align*}

error functions:

\begin{align*} \color{blue}{\delta_j^l} &= \frac{\partial C}{ \partial z_j^l} \end{align*}

$L$cost function

\begin{align*} C(w, b) &= \sum_k (y_k - a_k^L)^2 \end{align*}

ky

Feed-forward step

:

\begin{align*} \delta_j^L &= \frac{\partial C}{ \partial z_j^L} \\ &= \frac{\partial C}{ \partial a_j^L} \cdot \frac{\partial a_j^L}{ \partial z_j^L} \\ &= \frac{\partial C}{ \partial a_j^L} \cdot \sigma'(z_j^L) \end{align*}

Feed-forward step

:

\begin{align*} \frac{\partial C}{ \partial a_j^L} &= \frac{\partial}{ \partial a_j^L} \sum_k (y_k - a_k^L)^2 \\ &= 2 \cdot (a_j^L - y_j) \end{align*}

:

\begin{align*} \sigma'(z) &= \sigma(z) \cdot (1 - \sigma(z)) \end{align*}

Back-propagation step

$\delta_j^l$$\delta_j^{l+1}$

\begin{align*} \delta_j^l &= \frac{\partial C}{ \partial z_j^l} \\ &= \sum_k \frac{\partial C}{ \partial z_k^{l+1}} \cdot \frac{\partial z_k^{l+1}}{ \partial z_j^l} \\ &= \sum_k \delta_k^{l+1} \cdot \frac{\partial z_k^{l+1}}{ \partial z_j^l} \end{align*}

\begin{align*} z^{l+1}_k &= \sum_{i} w^{l+1}_{ki} a^l_i + b_k^{l+1} \\ &= \sum_i w^{l+1}_{ki} \sigma(z_i^l) + b_k^{l+1} \end{align*}

Back-propagation step

\begin{align*} \frac{\partial z^{l+1}_k}{ \partial z^{l}_j} &= \frac{\partial}{ \partial z^{l}_j} \left( \sum_i w^{l+1}_{ki} \sigma(z_j^l) + b_k^{l+1} \right) \\ &= w^{l+1}_{kj} \cdot \sigma'(z_j^l) \end{align*}

\begin{align*} \delta_j^l &= \sum_k \delta_k^{l+1} \cdot w^{l+1}_{kj} \cdot \sigma'(z_j^l) \end{align*}

errorsbias

\begin{align*} \delta_j^l &= \frac{\partial C}{ \partial z_j^l} \\ &=\frac{\partial C}{ \partial b_j^l} \cdot \frac{\partial b_j^l}{ \partial z_j^l} \\ &=\frac{\partial C}{ \partial b_j^l} \end{align*}

errorsweights

\begin{align*} \delta_j^l &= \frac{\partial C}{ \partial z_j^l} \\ &=\frac{\partial C}{ \partial w_{jk}^l} \cdot \frac{\partial w_{jk}^l}{ \partial z_j^l} \\ &=\frac{\partial C}{ \partial w_{jk}^l} \cdot \frac{1}{a^{l-1}_k} \end{align*}

\begin{align*} \frac{\partial C}{ \partial w_{jk}^l} &= a^{l-1}_k \delta_j^l \end{align*}

\begin{align*} \delta_j^L &= \nabla_{a^L} C \circ \sigma'(z^L) \\ \delta_j^l &= ((w^{l+1})^T \delta^{l+1}) \circ \sigma'(z^l) \\ \frac{\partial C}{\partial b^l_j} &= \delta^l_j \\ \frac{\partial C}{\partial w^l_{jk}} &= a^{l-1}_k \delta^l_j \end{align*}

$\circ$Hadamard product

The back-propagation algorithm

  • Select an element $i$ from the current minibatch and calculate the weighted inputs $z$ and activations $a$ for every layer using a forward pass through the network
  • Now, use these values to calculate the errors $\delta$ for each layer, starting at the last hidden layer and working backwards, using back-propagation
  • Calculate $\nabla_w C_i$ and $\nabla_b C_i$ using the last two equations
  • Repeat for all samples in the minibatch, to get: \begin{align*} \frac{\sum_{i \in M} \nabla_w C_i}{|M|} \approx \nabla_w C \quad \quad \quad \frac{\sum_{i \in M} \nabla_b C_i}{|M|} \approx \nabla_b C \end{align*}
  • Update the weights and biases by (the estimates of) $-\eta \cdot \nabla_w C$ and $-\eta \cdot \nabla_b C$, respectively
  • Repeat over every mini-batch, and for the desired number of epochs
